  "prompt": "Why did oil prices fall again in 2015?",
  "response": "Oil prices fell significantly in 2015 due to a combination of several factors:\n\n1. **Increased U.S. Production**: The United States experienced a boom in oil production due to advances in shale extraction technology, leading to a substantial increase in supply. This surge in output meant that the U.S. became one of the largest oil producers in the world, contributing to a global oversupply.\n\n2. **OPEC's Decision**: The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) chose not to cut its production levels in late 2014 and throughout 2015. This decision was partly a strategy to maintain market share and put pressure on higher-cost producers, particularly in the U.S.\n\n3. **Global Economic Slowdown**: There were concerns about slowing economic growth in major economies, including China. As demand for oil is closely tied to economic activity, expectations of lower demand contributed to falling prices.\n\n4. **Strong Dollar**: The value of the U.S. dollar strengthened in 2015, making oil more expensive for countries using other currencies. A stronger dollar can reduce demand for oil, further influencing prices downward.\n\n5. **Stockpiles and Inventories**: Inventory levels of crude oil rose significantly, particularly in the U.S., due to ongoing production increases. Higher inventories indicated an oversupplied market, leading to further price declines.\n\nThese factors combined led to a prolonged decline in oil prices throughout 2015, with prices dropping to levels not seen since the early 2000s.",
